<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-685-121  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 685 121.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Dec 3 1990 v219 n24 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber could keep the loop in shape for less. (public networkmaintained by fiber optics)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Warr, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Regional Bell holding companies (RBHC) expect fiber optic cablingto be easier and less expensive to maintain that copperconnections, yet it may take years for the fiber optic equipmentin the public network to justify these expectations, due in partto the fact that a learning curve for cable still challenges manyengineers.andP;  Deployment of the cable is also slow, with totalcoverage in the public network expected only around 2010.andP;  Whilethe cost of fiber maintenance in 1990 is estimated to be 10 to 20percent higher than the cost for maintaining copper cables, thesecosts may fall by 10 percent a year as more fiber is deployed.andO;Optical fiber is more resistant to environmental damages andcorrosion than is copper.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsBell Regional Holding CompaniesMaintenanceLearning Curve.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>